ty—a constellation of housing, temples, and other spaces providing possible futures. She explores the charitable trust as a technology of time, originating in the nineteenth century, one that structures intergenerational obligations for Mumbai’s Parsis, connecting past and present, the worldly and the sacred. By approaching Mumbai through the legal mechanism of the trust and the people who live within its bounds as well as those who challenge or support it, Vevaina offers a new pathway into exploring property, religion, and kinship in the urban global South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalismxReligious aspectszIndiazMumbai. 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszIndiazMumbai. 0aCapitalismzIndiazMumbaixReligious aspects. 0aCharitable uses, trusts, and foundationszIndiazMumbai. 0aParseesxCharitieszIndiazMumbai. 0aParseeszIndiazMumbaixCharities. 0aReligious trustszIndiazMumbai. 0aTrusts and trusteesxReligious aspectszIndiazMumbai. 0aTrusts and trusteeszIndiazMumbaixReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027515?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027515423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027515/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles